citeinfo.title: Trails Within and Around Rocky Mountain National Park

descript.abstract:
This data depicts trails in and around Rocky Mountain National Park. It is derived and developed from a number of sources. These include: 1:100000-scale USGS Digital Line Graph (DLG) data, the 1:50000-scale USGS map of Rocky Mountain National Park (40105-A4-PF-050), GPS (Global Positioning System) data, and heads-up digitizing using USGS DOQQ data as a backdrop.
Official names have been added and the sources of individual vectors identified.
descript.purpose: Data used and/or developed by the Rocky Mountain National Park GIS Program is used in the protection and management of Rocky Mountain National Park.

idinfo.useconst: Not for use at scales greater than 1:100000

attracc.attraccr: The attribute accuracy is deductively estimated to be "good". If a higher proof of data accuracy is required, do not use this data. User is advised to FULLY and CAREFULLY READ the "DISTRIBUTION LIABILITY" section of this metadata before using this data.

dataqual.complete: Data is considered complete. Some datasets are parkwide in scope, while others were developed and/or updated to address specific management concerns within particular spatial coordinates. Users of this data are advised to FULLY and CAREFULLY READ the "DISTRIBUTION LIABILITY" section of this metadata before using this data.

horizpa.horizpar: Horizontal accuracy varies depending on the source of individual components within the data. Data derived from USGS data (DLGs, DEMs, DOQQs) are assumed to meet National Map Accuracy standards, though extensive experience in using USGS data for the Rocky Mountain National Park area has shown that many data components have spatial errors exceeding the National Map Accuracy standards. Data produced from GPS (Global Positioning System) field data is assumed to be spatially accurate to within 2-5 meters.

procstep.procdesc:
A data layer consisting of 1:100000-scale USGS DLG data was queried and vectors were extracted to form the base of this data.
Additional vectors were added and some 1:100000-scale vectors were replaced with more accurate vectors digitized off of a paper copy of the 1:50000-scale USGS Rocky Mountain National Park Map (40105-A4-PF-050).
Additionally, some vectors were added and others adjusted using heads-up digitizing technique (digitizing off of the computer screen) using 1:12000- scale USGS DOQQs as a backdrop.
Additional vectors were added and some 1:100000-scale and 1:50000-scale vectors were replaced with more accurate vectors created by collecting GPS data. Line data were collected using Trimble GPS (Global Positioning System) equipment. All data was post-processed with Trimble's software resulting in an accuracy of 2-5 meters. Line features were edited and splined to clean up vectors using the ARC/INFO ARCEDIT module. Attributes were added to vectors using the ARC/INFO ARCEDIT module and ARC/INFO TABLES commands, though some attributes were attached to the data in the field using a pre-defined data dictionary. See <URL:http://www.trimble.com> for additional information regarding the specifications of Trimble equipment. Presently (July 1998) Rocky Mountain National Park is using a Trimble Pathfinder Professional and Trimble GeoExplorer IIs to collect GPS data.
Attributes were added to vectors using the ARC/INFO ARCEDIT module and ARC/INFO TABLES commands, though some attributes were attached to the data in the field using a pre-defined data dictionary when GPS data was collected.
Trails that have been closed or rerouted but that existed in the various data sources described above were extracted from this GIS data. The extracted vectors were saved in a new dataset using the ARC/INFO ARCEDIT command PUT, and deleted from this coverage.
The base template for this metadata created using ROMOMETA.AML, a locally modified version (modified June 1998) of FGDCMETA.AML ver. 1.2 05/14/98 on ARC/INFO data set /db/trans/trails

overview.eaover:
The first four items in the polygon attribute table (PAT), and the first seven items in the arc attribute table (AAT) are automatically generated by ARC/INFO software. Contact ESRI or read their literature for detailed descriptions of their internal file structure. ESRI (Environmental Systems Research Institute, Inc.) can be reached at: <URL:http://www.esri.com>
The TRAIL-NUM item is a text field populated with the official trail alphanumeric "number".
The HORSE-USE item is a text field that emulates a "YES/NO" data type. Values indicate whether or not horse use is permitted on the trail. Two values: >"Y" (Yes) >"N" (No)
The MILES item is populated by multiplying the LENGTH item by 0.0006213711922.
The FEET item is populated by multiplying the LENGTH item by 3.280839895.
The SOURCE item defines the source of individual components within the data set. Examples: >DOQQ - arcs, polygons, and/or points derived from features visible on >1:12000 USGS digital orthophotoquads >1:24K DLG - components originally from 1:24000 USGS digital line graph >data >GPS - arcs, polygons, and/or points collected with Global Positioning >System equipment >Other values might exist.
The TRAIL-NAME item is a text field populated by the official trail name.
